nRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81298"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of right ear pain, numbness and drooping of the right side of her face. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports noticing \u0027blisters\u0027 in her right ear yesterday and is now unable to completely close her right eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are vesicles in the right external ear canal and pinna. She has right-sided facial weakness affecting all muscles including the forehead (Image). Eye closure is incomplete on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left middle cerebral artery stroke","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Malignant otitis externa","Frey syndrome","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003ERamsay Hunt syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by reactivation of \u003Cem\u003EVaricella zoster virus\u003C/em\u003E in the geniculate ganglion. The combination of vesicles in the ear and ipsilateral lower motor neuron facial palsy is diagnostic. Early treatment with antivirals and corticosteroids within 72 hours of symptom onset improves outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft middle cerebral artery stroke\u003C/strong\u003E causing facial weakness would present with an upper motor neuron pattern of weakness, characteristically sparing the forehead due to bilateral cortical innervation. The presence of vesicles and the complete facial involvement make stroke unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant otitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe infection of the external ear canal, typically occurring in elderly diabetic patients. While it can cause facial nerve palsy, it presents with severe pain and purulent discharge rather than vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrey syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with gustatory sweating and facial flushing, typically following parotid surgery. It does not cause facial weakness or vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E rarely affects the facial nerve, and when it does, the weakness is typically bilateral and progressive. The acute onset and presence of vesicles make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplications of Ramsay Hunt syndrome can include incomplete resolution of facial weakness, post-herpetic neuralgia, and synkinesis. Eye care is important due to incomplete closure (lagophthalmos).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ramsay Hunt syndrome presents with facial nerve palsy and vesicles in the external ear due to reactivation of Varicella zoster virus.","Early treatment with antivirals and corticosteroids within 72 hours improves outcomes in Ramsay Hunt syndrome.","Lower motor neuron facial palsy affects the entire ipsilateral face including forehead, unlike upper motor neuron lesions which spare the forehead."],"references":["Sweeney CJ, Gilden DH. Ramsay Hunt syndrome. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry\u00a02001; 71:149\u201354. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11459884/","Sharma K, Tengsupakul S, Sanchez O, Phaltas R, Maertens P. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome with unilateral peripheral facial and bulbar palsy in a child: A case report. SAGE Open Med Case Rep. 2019 Mar 21;7:2050313X19838750. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30915222/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66640"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1573"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18667"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18667"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/952d6055-df89-4485-8b97-7aa1b14ac33d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/952d6055-df89-4485-8b97-7aa1b14ac33d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":437,"height":297}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66640"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T19:39:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T19:39:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1573"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81298"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags